title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER M1 CARBINE Late -- WWII 7.25-Million...Non-Import, Non-Rework
postcontent: Here's a late WWII production Winchester M1 Carbine that's in very good shape. This carbine is not an import, nor is it an arsenal rework. All parts on this carbine appear to be correct and original to the date of manufacture with the possible exception of the barrel band. The band is of the correct Type III variety with bayonet lug but normally one would expect to find it marked with a "C". Other than this one item, I believe all the parts have been together since day-1. The finish is original and the amount of wear is consistent throughout. Condition is very good and the original finish rates about 90% with some thinning to the blue finish on the round bolt and a little thinning to the finish on the barrel. There is no rust or pitting. The stock is correctly marked and of the correct Type III design. There are a few nicks and dings but no cracks or chips. The crossed cannons cartouche is original and well struck. The mechanics appear to be in perfect working order and the bore is excellent with bright rifling and a low muzzle erosion reading of under 1.0. It comes with an original sling, oiler, and Type II 15-round magazine. This carbine was part of Winchester's final serial block and was likely manufactured in mid-1945. A very good example, head and shoulders above most carbines you find today.

Length (Inches): 5.5
Close Focus (feet):

Features of Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope:

Waterproof: All Burris optics are proven to be absolutely waterproof. Each scope is submerged in water with a temperature of 50° C. The extremely hot water transfers its heat to the scope and the internal nitrogen expends 100% testing assures quality. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.
Fog proof: The nitrogen contained in the scope is of high quality (ultra dry, laboratory grade nitrogen), ultra pure and ultra clean. To be sure that all airborne moisture and surfaces moisture within a scope is evacuated, testing consists of 24 cycles of pressurizing the scope and then subjecting it to a vacuum. The tests are both cost & time intensive.
Shock proof: Burris scopes are subjected to extreme recoil tests. An impact machine is used to measure and duplicate the recoil pulse acceleration and duration. This machine has been calibrated and verified by an independent laboratory to replicate the wave frequencies and shock impulses that a scope is subjected to.
Ballistic Plex reticle - with a basic crosshair reticle, calculating hold-over is a mix of art, science and just plain luck, which is why Burris developed the Ballistic Plex reticle. The key is the copyrighted lower vertical crosshair. With most common hunting cartridges, a shooter can use the reticle to compensate for bullet drop and aim dead-on at targets from 100 to 500 yards out. The need for hold-over guesstimation is eliminated. Using it is simple. Start by sighting-in your rifle at 100 or 200 yards at your scope's highest magnification. Then, once you determine the distance to your target, select the appropriate ballistic line. Add slight hold-over or hold-under for in-between yardages and take the shot.
Includes binoculars!

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch -- HK41 .308 w/HK Accessories
postcontent: highly collectable Heckler & Koch HK41 .308 caliber semi-auto rifle. Very few imported into the United States; all were imported in 1966 by the Santa Fe Division of the Golden State Arms Corp. It is estimated that fewer than 400 rifle were produced and only a portion of these were imported to the U.S. The first generation HK41 has the G3 style "paddle" magazine release (in addition to the standard side release), and also features the lower push pin hole that was originally inteded for attachment of the selective fire G3 trigger group. There featuresmade it too easy to illegally convert the rifle to full auto and were deleted in the later production HK41 and HK91 rifles. First generation HK41 rifle were "grandfathered" by the ATF, and are legal to own in their orginal configuaration. Condition: NRA Excellant. All numbers match, bright bore. Very minor handling marks, scratches. Original HK Accessories: Nine Magazines, Bi-Pod, Bayonet w/sheath and case, Two Slings-1 leather/1 Cotton, Sight Tool, Small Parts Kit, Extra Flash Hider, Magazine Loader, Original Owners Manual, Assorted HK Literature
